Application Lifecycle Management

1. Rolling Updates and Rollback
While deploying a deployment, Replicaset will deploy the pods with the replicaset counts. 
If we update the deployment with Image version or any updates in the deployment, rolling update strategy takes place. 

Rolling update strategy:
Recreate update strategy: Delete the existing instance and recreate the new instances. (application down - impact downtime) 
Rolling update strategy: Default strategy, It will delete and update one by one pods. (No impact)

Rollback:
If we face any issue with the updated deployment, need to rollback to the older version.


Commands:
# kubectl create -f deploy myapp
# kubectl apply -f deploy myapp or kubect set image deploy myapp my-container-name=updatedimageversion

# kubectl rollout undo deploy myapp

# kubectl rollout status deploy myapp
# kubectl rollout history status deploy myapp

Important:
Recreate/RollingUpdate configuration in yaml
deployment.yml
spec:
 strategy:
    type: Recreate/RollingUpdate

2. Configure Applications 
A. Configuring commands and arguments in the application
B. Configuring Environment varibales
C. Configuring configmaps

A. Configuring commands and arguments in the application
Docker has CMD and Entrypoint to run the docker commands while creating the container. CMD can overwritten and Entrypoint is main purpose to run.
Kubernetes has Command and Arguments to run the kuberenets commands while createing pods. We can set both arguments and commands in yaml file.
Example: 
To run the java applciation in dev environment. Java info in entrypoint and env info in CMD.
# docker run my-java-app
runs the java in the container with dev env

# docker run my-java-app prod
runs the java in the container with prod env

Command (entrypoint) # kubectl run nginx --image=nginx --command python
Arguments (CMD) # kubectl run nginx --image=nginx pink

Important:
Command configuration in yaml
spec:
  containers:
  - name: ubuntu
    image: ubuntu
    command: 
      - "sleep"
      - "5000"

B. Configuring env variables 
Configuring env varibales in the kubernetes is adding a env varaibles to the container where the application is deployed.
Important:
spec:
  containers:
  - name: ubuntu
    image: ubuntu
  env:
  - name: APP_COLOR
    value: Pink

C. Configuring ConfigMaps
Create configmap and add env data key/values in it.
Now Inject configmaps details in the pod.

Important:
creating configmaps
kubectl create configmap webapp-config-map /
--from-literal=APP_COLOR=darkblue /
--from-literal=APP_OTHER=disregard



injecting configmaps into pods
spec:
  containers:
  - env:
    - name: APP_COLOR
      ValueFrom:
      configMapKeyRef:
        name: webapp-config-app
        key: APP_COLOR














